$$ \int \left\| \sum_{i \in A} X_i \right\|^{2m} \, d\mu \leq \text{marcinkiewiczZygmundConst}(2m) \cdot \int \left( \sum_{i \in A} \|X_i\|^2 \right)^m \, d\mu $$

To prove this, we can use the fact that for independent random variables with mean zero, the $L^p$ norm of the sum is related to the $L^2$ norms of the individual variables. Specifically, for $p = 2m$, we can use the inequality:
$$ \mathbb{E}\left\| \sum_{i=1}^n X_i \right\|^{2m} \leq C \cdot \mathbb{E}\left( \sum_{i=1}^n \|X_i\|^2 \right)^m $$
where $C$ is a constant.

