The proof strategy is to use the fact that for independent mean-zero random variables, the $L^p$-norm of the sum is related to the $L^{p/2}$-norm of the sum of squared norms. Specifically, we can use the inequality $\| \sum X_i \|_{L^{2m}} \leq C \cdot (\sum \|X_i\|^2)^{m}$, where $C = 2^{m} \cdot \binom{2m}{m}$.

